1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,280
Instructor: In this short video,

2
00:00:02,280 --> 00:00:05,400
we will see the different service lifetimes

3
00:00:05,400 --> 00:00:10,050
when it comes to dependency injection in .NET Core.

4
00:00:10,050 --> 00:00:13,290
Now, you do not have to program this along with me.

5
00:00:13,290 --> 00:00:16,650
I just want you guys to watch the next 10 minutes,

6
00:00:16,650 --> 00:00:20,550
and understand what are the different service lifetimes

7
00:00:20,550 --> 00:00:23,220
in dependency injection.

8
00:00:23,220 --> 00:00:25,800
Before we take a look at any example,

9
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:28,530
let me quickly give you a rough idea

10
00:00:28,530 --> 00:00:32,490
on what each lifetime is responsible for.

11
00:00:32,490 --> 00:00:36,540
Transient lifetime is the simplest one among all of them,

12
00:00:36,540 --> 00:00:39,600
and it is also one of the safest one.

13
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:41,040
Transient basically means

14
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:43,770
that whenever we want any implementation,

15
00:00:43,770 --> 00:00:47,340
create a new object, and give that new object.

16
00:00:47,340 --> 00:00:50,520
You never have to reuse an existing object.

17
00:00:50,520 --> 00:00:52,950
Every time a service is requested,

18
00:00:52,950 --> 00:00:55,443
a new implementation is created.

19
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:58,680
After that, we have the scoped,

20
00:00:58,680 --> 00:01:02,190
where it depends on the HTTP request.

21
00:01:02,190 --> 00:01:06,120
So whenever an HTTP request is sent to the server,

22
00:01:06,120 --> 00:01:10,740
that time for that scope, one lifetime will be created,

23
00:01:10,740 --> 00:01:14,820
and then the same object or same service is used

24
00:01:14,820 --> 00:01:19,530
wherever in that request the service is requested.

25
00:01:19,530 --> 00:01:22,140
So let's say for one single page load,

26
00:01:22,140 --> 00:01:24,660
we are calling a service 10 times.

27
00:01:24,660 --> 00:01:27,930
It'll only create that object one time,

28
00:01:27,930 --> 00:01:32,930
and it'll use that same object 10 times in that one request.

29
00:01:33,510 --> 00:01:36,150
But then if a next request comes in,

30
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:39,033
then a new implementation is created.

31
00:01:39,990 --> 00:01:42,270
And finally, we have singleton,

32
00:01:42,270 --> 00:01:44,670
where one implementation is created

33
00:01:44,670 --> 00:01:47,640
for the lifetime of the application.

34
00:01:47,640 --> 00:01:50,100
So once the application starts,

35
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:54,000
we create an object of that service or an implementation,

36
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,360
and that is used for all the upcoming request

37
00:01:57,360 --> 00:01:59,853
unless you restart the application.

38
00:02:01,170 --> 00:02:04,383
So to give you a rough idea, again, transient,

39
00:02:05,315 --> 00:02:08,490
new service is created every single time,

40
00:02:08,490 --> 00:02:13,490
for scoped, new service will be created once per request,

41
00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:17,430
and for singleton, new service will be created

42
00:02:17,430 --> 00:02:20,283
once per application lifetime.

43
00:02:21,120 --> 00:02:24,630
Now, scoped is one of the most recommended approach

44
00:02:24,630 --> 00:02:26,580
for web application.

45
00:02:26,580 --> 00:02:31,380
Because of that, a service will be created on each request.

46
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:33,900
But even with all of this overview,

47
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:36,393
things might be a little complicated.

48
00:02:37,260 --> 00:02:39,720
So let me explain that a little more

49
00:02:39,720 --> 00:02:41,883
with a real world example.

50
00:02:42,930 --> 00:02:45,090
Let me switch to Visual Studio,

51
00:02:45,090 --> 00:02:48,333
and we will be creating an MVC application.

52
00:02:49,260 --> 00:02:51,510
I will give it a name of DI_Service_Lifetime,

53
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:54,753
and let me create that.

54
00:02:56,280 --> 00:03:00,120
In the project here, let me create a new folder

55
00:03:00,120 --> 00:03:02,163
for services.

56
00:03:03,270 --> 00:03:05,937
In there, let me create three interface

57
00:03:05,937 --> 00:03:08,880
for the three service that we have.

58
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:11,763
So the first one will be IScoped.

59
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:17,943
Let me add a new one here, that will be singleton.

60
00:03:18,900 --> 00:03:22,443
And finally, we will be adding the transient.

61
00:03:23,561 --> 00:03:26,042
These are just the interface name.

62
00:03:26,042 --> 00:03:28,260
We have not added any functionality.

63
00:03:28,260 --> 00:03:31,023
In there, let me add a method, GetGuid,

64
00:03:31,890 --> 00:03:34,530
which will return a random guid.

65
00:03:34,530 --> 00:03:37,083
So the return type will be string.

66
00:03:39,030 --> 00:03:40,810
Perfect, I will add that

67
00:03:41,646 --> 00:03:44,043
in all the three interface that we added.

68
00:03:45,090 --> 00:03:49,173
Now we need to add implementation of these three interface.

69
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:53,430
Implementation will be pretty simple.

70
00:03:53,430 --> 00:03:57,590
Let me add a class here for the SingletonGuidService

71
00:03:58,470 --> 00:04:02,610
that will implement the ISingletonGuidService,

72
00:04:02,610 --> 00:04:04,413
implement the interface.

73
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,190
Here, let me create a private read-only guid

74
00:04:10,152 --> 00:04:12,873
with the name of Id, and in the constructor,

75
00:04:13,803 --> 00:04:16,173
Id, we will say Guid.NewGuid.

76
00:04:17,279 --> 00:04:18,723
In the function here,

77
00:04:19,599 --> 00:04:22,173
we just want to return Id.ToString.

78
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:25,200
That looks good.

79
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:27,780
Let me create the same implementation

80
00:04:27,780 --> 00:04:31,320
for the other two interface that we have.

81
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:35,673
Let me add a class which will be ScopedGuidService,

82
00:04:36,657 --> 00:04:40,107
and that will implement the IScopedGuidService.

83
00:04:41,730 --> 00:04:45,660
I can copy everything here, paste it,

84
00:04:45,660 --> 00:04:48,660
and we will change the constructor name.

85
00:04:48,660 --> 00:04:50,250
Looks good.

86
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:53,823
Let me add the last one, which is TransientGuidService.

87
00:04:56,070 --> 00:05:00,123
Let me copy and paste it in here.

88
00:05:01,050 --> 00:05:05,880
And this will implement the ITransientGuidService.

89
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,980
So now we have three interface,

90
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:11,610
and their corresponding three implementation.

91
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:13,440
That looks good.

92
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:17,700
But when we register the services to Program.cs,

93
00:05:17,700 --> 00:05:22,700
we have to write the lifecycle to which we want to register.

94
00:05:22,890 --> 00:05:25,506
So in the add service here,

95
00:05:25,506 --> 00:05:28,980
we will say builder.Services.add,

96
00:05:28,980 --> 00:05:32,643
and then we have to write what lifecycle we want to use.

97
00:05:33,874 --> 00:05:36,513
We have scoped, transient, and singleton.

98
00:05:37,350 --> 00:05:40,110
In singleton, we will have the interface,

99
00:05:40,110 --> 00:05:43,170
which is ISingletonGuidService,

100
00:05:43,170 --> 00:05:48,170
and implementation is inside the SingletonGuidService.

101
00:05:48,180 --> 00:05:51,000
That is how we register a service

102
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,300
to the dependency injection container.

103
00:05:54,300 --> 00:05:58,293
We will also register the transient and scoped service.

104
00:05:59,310 --> 00:06:00,240
Perfect.

105
00:06:00,240 --> 00:06:01,560
So it is exactly same

106
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:05,460
like if we were registering DP context to the container,

107
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:07,950
and then when we have to use that,

108
00:06:07,950 --> 00:06:10,533
we will do that inside the HomeController.

109
00:06:11,670 --> 00:06:14,790
Before we start using that, right here,

110
00:06:14,790 --> 00:06:17,910
let me create six private fields.

111
00:06:17,910 --> 00:06:20,220
Two will be for the scoped service,

112
00:06:20,220 --> 00:06:23,850
two for singleton, and two for transient.

113
00:06:23,850 --> 00:06:26,910
We have scoped one, two, singleton one, two,

114
00:06:26,910 --> 00:06:28,593
and transient one, two.

115
00:06:29,670 --> 00:06:34,110
Next, what we want is implementation of these interface.

116
00:06:34,110 --> 00:06:37,530
We registered that in Program.cs right here,

117
00:06:37,530 --> 00:06:39,725
so basically we are saying

118
00:06:39,725 --> 00:06:42,485
that when someone asks for an implementation

119
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:46,410
of ISingletonGuidService, we are telling the .NET framework

120
00:06:46,410 --> 00:06:49,530
that provide them the implementation that is there

121
00:06:49,530 --> 00:06:51,603
in the SingletonGuidService.

122
00:06:52,470 --> 00:06:56,709
But there we are telling that use the AddSingleton

123
00:06:56,709 --> 00:06:57,759
that is the lifetime.

124
00:06:58,995 --> 00:07:01,110
So when we want to use the implementation

125
00:07:01,110 --> 00:07:05,935
inside the constructor here, we can directly ask .NET Core

126
00:07:05,935 --> 00:07:09,810
that we need the implementation of IScopedGuidService,

127
00:07:09,810 --> 00:07:13,470
and we will call that as scopedGuid.

128
00:07:13,470 --> 00:07:16,410
Then we want another implementation of that.

129
00:07:16,410 --> 00:07:21,410
So scopedGuid1, comma, we will have scopedGuid2.

130
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:24,240
And similarly, we want the implementation

131
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:27,780
for singleton and transient service.

132
00:07:27,780 --> 00:07:30,377
So these are the implementation

133
00:07:30,377 --> 00:07:31,860
that .NET framework will provide

134
00:07:31,860 --> 00:07:36,000
based on what we registered in Program.cs.

135
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,970
Then we have to assign these implementation

136
00:07:38,970 --> 00:07:42,573
to the local variable that we have right here.

137
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:48,170
For that, we will say _singleton1 is equal to singleton1,

138
00:07:49,246 --> 00:07:50,883
and same for everything else.

139
00:07:51,972 --> 00:07:54,150
I can change this to be scoped1

140
00:07:54,150 --> 00:07:56,523
rather than scopedGuid here.

141
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:00,090
Perfect, looks good.

142
00:08:00,090 --> 00:08:02,790
So we have this implementation.

143
00:08:02,790 --> 00:08:07,080
On there, we can call the method, which is GetGuid.

144
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:09,420
Rather than making anything fancy,

145
00:08:09,420 --> 00:08:12,960
let me use a string builder for messages here,

146
00:08:12,960 --> 00:08:15,750
and I will append to that message

147
00:08:15,750 --> 00:08:17,853
using string interpolation.

148
00:08:19,380 --> 00:08:21,870
So first, I will say Transient 1,

149
00:08:21,870 --> 00:08:24,300
and then we will display the value

150
00:08:24,300 --> 00:08:27,873
using _transient1.GetGuid.

151
00:08:30,270 --> 00:08:35,270
We have that method, and after that, let me add a new line.

152
00:08:36,659 --> 00:08:38,970
So perfect, that looks good.

153
00:08:38,970 --> 00:08:43,970
For the first transient, copy and paste that once again.

154
00:08:44,280 --> 00:08:47,970
We want to display the transient2.GetGuid.

155
00:08:47,970 --> 00:08:50,523
And let me add one more new line there.

156
00:08:52,590 --> 00:08:56,250
Copy these, paste it two more times.

157
00:08:56,250 --> 00:08:58,533
Next, we want this scoped1.

158
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:04,653
scoped1, scoped2, _scoped1, _scoped2.

159
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:11,343
And finally, we need singleton.

160
00:09:12,300 --> 00:09:13,133
Perfect.

161
00:09:14,230 --> 00:09:15,829
When we return back,

162
00:09:15,829 --> 00:09:17,753
we do not want to return back to a view,

163
00:09:17,753 --> 00:09:19,080
we just want to return okay

164
00:09:19,080 --> 00:09:23,163
and display the message, .ToString, on the screen.

165
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:27,630
So now we need to think about what will happen.

166
00:09:27,630 --> 00:09:30,880
All of them have basically the same GetGuid method

167
00:09:32,026 --> 00:09:33,540
which returns a random guid,

168
00:09:33,540 --> 00:09:35,670
but the only thing that is different

169
00:09:35,670 --> 00:09:39,033
is on how the lifecycle have been registered.

170
00:09:40,110 --> 00:09:43,803
So let me run this, and see that in action.

171
00:09:45,780 --> 00:09:46,953
And perfect.

172
00:09:47,918 --> 00:09:49,950
We have something right here.

173
00:09:49,950 --> 00:09:51,660
You can see when we are working

174
00:09:51,660 --> 00:09:55,530
with the transient request here, the guids are different,

175
00:09:55,530 --> 00:09:57,990
but when we have scoped or singleton,

176
00:09:57,990 --> 00:09:59,730
they are the same.

177
00:09:59,730 --> 00:10:02,160
As we know, singleton stays same

178
00:10:02,160 --> 00:10:05,940
for the lifecycle of the application.

179
00:10:05,940 --> 00:10:08,970
So even when we refresh the application,

180
00:10:08,970 --> 00:10:11,520
scoped and transient will be different,

181
00:10:11,520 --> 00:10:15,390
but singleton will always stay the same.

182
00:10:15,390 --> 00:10:17,910
You can see when I'm refreshing here,

183
00:10:17,910 --> 00:10:21,060
transient is getting updated along with scoped,

184
00:10:21,060 --> 00:10:24,243
but singleton always stays the same.

185
00:10:25,410 --> 00:10:27,752
And then for scoped here,

186
00:10:27,752 --> 00:10:30,000
you can see every time for a single request,

187
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:33,931
it gets a new value, but for one request,

188
00:10:33,931 --> 00:10:36,393
the value stays the same in both of them.

189
00:10:37,230 --> 00:10:42,230
But in transient, for any time a guid is requested,

190
00:10:42,241 --> 00:10:43,920
it calls a new guid.

191
00:10:43,920 --> 00:10:47,373
So that means every time when a transient is called,

192
00:10:48,295 --> 00:10:52,050
it basically gives a new implementation of that service.

193
00:10:52,050 --> 00:10:54,362
When it comes to scoped,

194
00:10:54,362 --> 00:10:57,660
the implementation stays same for one request.

195
00:10:57,660 --> 00:11:01,200
If in that one request, we are calling this 10 times,

196
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:03,420
we will get the same service,

197
00:11:03,420 --> 00:11:07,500
but for the next time, it will get you a different service

198
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:09,333
when you are working with scoped.

199
00:11:10,770 --> 00:11:13,710
So with that, you can see how transient, scoped,

200
00:11:13,710 --> 00:11:15,750
and singleton are different

201
00:11:15,750 --> 00:11:19,563
when it comes to dependency injection service lifetime.

